goals.question: What is the distribution of income per capita across different regions?
goals.visualization: Box plot of income_per_capita by region
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the spread of income per capita across different regions and identify any outliers or differences in the distribution.

goals.question: What is the relationship between income per capita and total population?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of income_per_capita and total
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify any correlation between income per capita and total population, and understand if there is any relationship between the two variables.

goals.question: What is the distribution of income per capita by group?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the distribution of income per capita across different groups and identify any differences or similarities in the distribution.

goals.question: What is the distribution of total population by region?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of total by region
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the distribution of total population across different regions and identify any differences or similarities in the distribution.

goals.question: What is the proportion of each group in the dataset?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the proportion of each group in the dataset and identify any imbalances or biases in the data.

code:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['region'] = data['region'].astype('category')
    data.boxplot(column='income_per_capita', by='region', figsize=(10,6))
    plt.title('What is the distribution of income per capita across different regions?', wrap=True)
    plt.ylabel('Income per capita')
    plt.xlabel('Region')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.scatter(data['income_per_capita'], data['total'])
    ax.set_xlabel('Income per capita')
    ax.set_ylabel('Total population')
    ax.set_title('What is the relationship between income per capita and total population?')
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data = data.dropna(subset=['income_per_capita'])
    groups = data['group'].unique()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    for group in groups:
        ax.hist(data[data['group'] == group]['income_per_capita'], alpha=0.5, label=group)
    ax.set_xlabel('Income per capita')
    ax.set_ylabel('Frequency')
    ax.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of income per capita by group?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data = data.groupby('region')['total'].sum().reset_index()
    plt.bar(data['region'], data['total'])
    plt.title('What is the distribution of total population by region?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    group_data = data.groupby('group').size()
    plt.pie(group_data, labels=group_data.index, autopct='%1.1f%%')
    plt.title('What is the proportion of each group in the dataset?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
